  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense under most legal systems around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (such as funds obtained through illegal activities like drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or organized crime) appear legitimate by concealing their true origin. This activity is criminalized to combat organized crime, terrorism financing, and other illegal activities that undermine the integrity of financial systems.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Penalties for money laundering can include substantial fines and lengthy prison sentences, depending on the severity of the offense.\n\nSimilarly, in the European Union, money laundering is addressed under the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**, and in many countries, it is criminalized under national legislation aligned with international standards set by organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is unequivocally a criminal act and is prosecuted under criminal law globally.",
